==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*tīwa-'', from Indo-European ''*dhyeu-'' ‘god’.  Cognate with Old Norse [[Tyr|Týr]], Old High German [[Zio|Zīo]], Gothic [[𐍄𐌴𐌶]].  The IE root is also the source of Greek [[Ζευς]], Latin [[deus]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /ti:w/

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
'''Tīw''' ''m''
# the god Tiw, a Germanic god of warfare, identified with the Roman god [[Mars]]
# the runic character ᛏ (/t/)

